topics.content:
I'm sending this email to all, so we can all learn from this example. LuxUrias had an RP-only-eligible player scheduled for start. To use him, he had to put him in an RP slot. He asked to clarify how to play him and what were his options by being limited to only two active RPs on that day. I responded:

Good job, you found an anomoly in the system! I see I am getting back to you too late but you properly played him any way. As stated in the rule, the intent is not to have more than 3 MLB-active-RPs in any given day, so you acted properly and lived up to the intent of the rule. Thanks!

Since he is an RP-eligible-only player you will have to start him from an RP slot. I would allow and not penalize you if you had an SP-eligible working-RP (like your Pomeranz OR Castillo...NOT both) in an SP slot so you have 3 MLB-eligible RPs active in one day.

The RP rule is to prevent exploiting RPs who are SP eligible, not punish for having an RP-only act as an SP. 

I will note that if you have an RP-only acting as an SP, and you have 3 other RPs that are RP-only eligible, you will have to choose who to play and lose out on one potential point-accumulating day for an RP. After a couple starts (for 2020, it is 2 starts), the RP-only will gain SP eligibility and the problem would be solved. 

Thanks for the question and good luck.

Hey Christian. Thanks for the input.  

The reason I did this was most sources I've read were saying a month of off, then 10-14 days of spring training then season begins early May. There is certainly going to be a month without baseball, then a reassessment. That is why I chose the new Keeper/Draft dates as a holding spot.

Once they announce the beginning of ST, there will be at least a few days if not a week before players report. 

My plan is to announce several Draft Dates to vote on right when we get a confirmation of the MLB schedule. Also announce a Keeper Date for a couple days or a week at most from when MLB announces their schedule. 

I do agree that we had a good Day/Date chosen and I hope it doesn't blow up in my face. We had 8 of 10 consenting, but we had two unknowns. I'm hoping for 10/10 next time!

I think most leagues are postponing their drafts. Where many of us are in multiple leagues, it appears the entire draft season is getting pushed at least a month, so I am following the herd on this one. If we had 10/10 on the draft date/time, I might have kept that date.

topics.content:
Standard ESPN RULES apply with the addition of 'THE RP RULE'.

A reminder, ESPN uses a soft limit of 200 starts per season. 'Soft Limit' means that on the day when the 200th start is attained, any and all starts that day will count. Example, if you have 199 starts accrued and you start 5 SPs on a following day, ALL 5 starts will count and you will end up with 204 starts for the season. After the day the limit is reached or exceeded, all other starts on following days will not count.

THE RP RULE: 
We feel there is a small but possible exploit of RP usage where only a few MLB-active RPs have SP eligibility and can be used in the SP slots under ESPN rules, thereby giving an owner an unfair advantage. The rule is an attempt to close this loophole. Please abide by the INTENT of this rule as any attempt to circumvent this rule with unforeseen methods will be considered a violation of these rules and you will be penalized accordingly.

The simple rule for this league is as follows. [b]An owner is allowed to have only THREE total MLB-active RPs in their active, non-bench daily slots at any given time.[/b]

An MLB-active RP is defined as a pitcher who is not in the starting rotation of a team and pitches mostly out of the bullpen, except for emergency spot starting.

If you have an MLB-active RP who has ONLY SP eligibility, then you MUST leave an RP slot vacant on the days that you place this SP-only eligible RP in an SP slot.

The penalty for playing 4 or more MLB-active RPs in active slots on any given day will be the removal of all points accrued for ALL MLB-ACTIVE RPs IN ACTIVE RP OR SP SLOTS for that day. Multiple intentional infractions can lead to owner removal. 

[b]There is NO penalty for a MLB-rotation-active SP who makes a random relief appearance.[/b]

messages.content:
[b]RP RULE CLARIFICATION:[/b] If you have an RP-eligible-only player you will have to start him from an RP slot. I would allow and not penalize you if you had an SP-eligible working-RP in an SP slot so you have 3 MLB-eligible RPs active in one day.

The RP rule is to prevent exploiting RPs who are SP eligible, not punish for having an RP-only act as an SP. 

I will note that if you have an RP-only acting as an SP, and you have 3 other RPs that are RP-only eligible, you will have to choose who to play and lose out on one potential point-accumulating day for an RP. After a couple starts (for 2020, it is 2 starts), the RP-only will gain SP eligibility and the problem would be solved.
